HEADWORD: Progenitor
<hw>Pro*gen"i*tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>progeniteur</ets>, L. <ets>progenitor</ets>, fr.
<ets>progignere</ets>, <ets>progenitum</ets>, to bring forth, to beget;
<ets>pro</ets> forth + <ets>gignere</ets> to beget. See <er>Gender</er>
kind.]</ety> <def>An ancestor in the direct line; a
forefather.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And reverence thee their great <qex>progenitor</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Progenitorship</ent>⟦br⟧
